# Zod v4 Gotchas

## `z.record()` requires TWO arguments

In Zod v4, `z.record(schema)` with ONE argument treats that arg as the **key type**, not the value type (breaking change from v3). The value type is left `undefined`, causing a runtime crash when the AI SDK or anything else tries to convert the schema to JSON Schema:

```
TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading '_zod')
```

```typescript
// ❌ BROKEN in Zod v4 — z.string() becomes the key type, valueType is undefined
z.record(z.string())
z.record(z.any())
z.record(z.unknown())

// ✅ Always pass two args: z.record(keyType, valueType)
z.record(z.string(), z.string())   // string keys, string values
z.record(z.string(), z.unknown())  // string keys, any values
z.record(z.string(), z.number())   // string keys, number values
```

## AI SDK tool `inputSchema`: use `jsonSchema()` for open records

The AI SDK's `asSchema()` wraps Zod schemas with `addAdditionalPropertiesToJsonSchema()`, which **overrides `additionalProperties` to `false` on all nested objects**. This breaks any tool parameter that needs to accept arbitrary key-value pairs (e.g., `query_params`, `body`).

Use `jsonSchema()` from `ai` directly when a tool parameter needs `additionalProperties`:

```typescript
import { jsonSchema, tool } from 'ai'

// ❌ Even with correct 2-arg z.record(), AI SDK will set additionalProperties: false
// making the schema reject any key-value pairs the LLM tries to pass
tool({
  inputSchema: z.object({
    query_params: z.record(z.string(), z.string()).optional(),
    body: z.record(z.string(), z.unknown()).optional(),
  }),
})

// ✅ Use jsonSchema() to preserve additionalProperties correctly
tool({
  inputSchema: jsonSchema<{
    query_params?: Record<string, string>
    body?: Record<string, unknown>
  }>({
    type: 'object',
    properties: {
      query_params: { type: 'object', additionalProperties: { type: 'string' } },
      body: { type: 'object', additionalProperties: true },
    },
    additionalProperties: false,
  }),
})
```
